shaughlin, County Meath, Ireland":"Killeen, Dunshaughlin, County Meath, Irland","Dublin, County Dublin, Ireland":"Dublin, County Dublin, Irland","St Mary's, County Dublin, Ireland":"St Mary's, County Dublin, Irland","Dublin, Dublin, Ireland":"Dublin, County Dublin, Irland"},"nl":{"ABT 1157–":"1157–Overleden","1157–Female":"1157–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1157–1215":"1157–1215","1189–1248":"1189–1248","1193–1218":"1193–1218","–1218":"–1218","1130–Male":"1130–Overleden","1192–1219":"1192–1219","1130":"1130","1193":"1193","abt 1189":"circa 1189","1192":"1192","1248":"1248","1215":"1215","1157":"1157","1167":"1167","1189":"1189","ABT 1157":"1157","1188":"1188","Abt 1193":"1193","1219":"1219","1218":"1218","Killeen, Dunshaughlin, County Meath, Ireland":"Killeen, Dunshaughlin, County Meath, Ierland","Dublin, County Dublin, Ireland":"Dublin, County Dublin, Ierland","St Mary's, County Dublin, Ireland":"St Mary's, County Dublin, Ierland","Dublin, Dublin, Ireland":"Dublin, County Dublin, Ierland"},"en":{"ABT 1157–":"1157–Deceased","1157–Female":"1157–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1157–1215":"1157–1215","1189–1248":"1189–1248","1193–1218":"1193–1218","–1218":"–1218","1130–Male":"1130–Deceased","1192–1219":"1192–1219","1130":"1130","1193":"1193","abt 1189":"about 1189","1192":"1192","1248":"1248","1215":"1215","1157":"1157","1167":"1167","1189":"1189","ABT 1157":"1157","1188":"1188","Abt 1193":"1193","1219":"1219","1218":"1218","Killeen, Dunshaughlin, County Meath, Ireland":"Killeen, Dunshaughlin, County Meath, Ireland","Dublin, County Dublin, Ireland":"Dublin, County Dublin, Ireland","St Mary's, County Dublin, Ireland":"St Mary's, County Dublin, Ireland","Dublin, Dublin, Ireland":"Dublin, County Dublin, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Petite","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Celestine, Jacques.","French: from the feminine form of   Petit   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."],"variants":[{"name":"Petit","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Alain, Michel, Normand, Mireille, Philippe, Pierre, Achille, Armand, Jean Claude, Jean Jacques, Ketly, Adrien.","French, Walloon, Catalan, English, Jewish (from southern France), West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian: from (Old) French, Catalan, and Middle English <i>petit</i> ‘small’, hence a nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a big man), or a distinguishing name for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name. Compare   Little  ,   Petee  , and   Petite  .","History: Charles Petit from Anneville-Ambourville in Seine-Maritime, France, married Jeanne Rossignol (Martin and Renée Desjardins) in Quebec City, QC, in 1670. Nicolas Petit <i>dit</i> Lapré/Laprée from Le Gué-d'Alleré in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie Pouponnel in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1656. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Gobin from Lyon in Rhône married Marguerite Véron in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1692. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Saint-Pierre from Évreux in Eure, France, married Judith Miville in Quebec City, QC, in 1758; see also   St. Pierre  . — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Anglicized in pronunciation and respelled   Mary .  This French form was reintroduced into the English-speaking world as a separate name in the 19th century, and is still pronounced more or less in the French manner, although sometimes with the stress on the first syllable. It is now often used in combination with other names such as <i>Ellie</i>, <i>Chloe</i>, and <i>Lisa</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355923,"age":10,"year":"1167","julianDay":2147298,"description":"Arrival of Normans at Baginbun in Co. Wexford thus started 800 year struggle between English and Irish.","jurisdictionLevel":3}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda Marie Petite was born in 1157, in Dublin, County Dublin, Ireland, her father, Lord Adam de Petite, was 27 and her mother, Lucy Ledwych, was -35. She married Geoffrey Mo'r Cusack in 1188, in Dublin, County Dublin, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in Killeen, Dunshaughlin, County Meath, Ireland."},"et":{"ABT 1157–":"1157–Surnud","1157–Female":"1157–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1157–1215":"1157–1215","1189–1248":"1189–1248","1193–1218":"1193–1218","–1218":"–1218","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1192–1219":"1192–1219","1130":"1130","1193":"1193","abt 1189":"umbes 1189","1192":"1192","1248":"1248","1215":"1215","1157":"1157","1167":"1167","1189":"1189","ABT 1157":"1157","1188":"1188","Abt 1193":"1193","1219":"1219","1218":"1218","Killeen, Dunshaughlin, County Meath, Ireland":"Killeen, Dunshaughlin, County Meath, Iirimaa","Dublin, County Dublin, Ireland":"Dublin, County Dublin, Iirimaa"